SIMPLE: chock
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Chock
<hw>Chock</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Chocked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Chocking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To stop or fasten, as with a
wedge, or block; to scotch; <as>as, to <ex>chock</ex> a wheel or
cask</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Chock</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Chock
<hw>Chock</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To fill up, as a cavity.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The woodwork . . . exactly <xex>chocketh</xex> into
joints.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Chock</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Chock
<hw>Chock</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A wedge, or block made to
fit in any space which it is desired to fill, esp. something to steady a
cask or other body, or prevent it from moving, by fitting into the space
around or beneath it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A heavy casting of metal, usually
fixed near the gunwale. It has two short horn-shaped arms curving
inward, between which ropes or hawsers may pass for towing, mooring,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Chock</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Chock
<hw>Chock</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>Entirely; quite;
<as>as, <ex>chock</ex> home; <ex>chock</ex> aft</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Chock</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Chock
<hw>Chock</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>choquer</ets>. Cf.
<er>Shock</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <def>To encounter.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Chock</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Chock
<hw>Chock</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An encounter.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Chockablock</ent>⟦br⟧
